<body>
  <header>
    <div class="badge"><span class="dot"></span> Usability Test Documentation – Quiet Bloom</div>
    <h1>Heuristic Evaluation & User Test Plan</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">
      This page summarizes the heuristic evaluation (Nielsen’s 10 heuristics) and the planned user test to assess
      whether Quiet Bloom supports users in understanding and predicting mood, pain, energy levels, and period flow.
    </p>
  </header>

  <main>
    <div class="grid two">
      <section>
        <h2><span class="icon">1</span> Heuristic Evaluation</h2>
        <p class="muted">
          Before running the user test, a heuristic evaluation will be conducted based on Nielsen’s 10 Usability Heuristics.
          The evaluation focuses on:
        </p>
        <div class="pillrow" aria-label="Focus areas">
          <span class="pill">Calendar navigation</span>
          <span class="pill">Adding daily entries</span>
          <span class="pill">Statistics & predictions</span>
          <span class="pill">Journal overview</span>
        </div>

        <div class="tablewrap" role="region" aria-label="Heuristic findings table">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr>
                <th style="width: 140px;">Page</th>
                <th>Problem</th>
                <th style="width: 210px;">Heuristic</th>
                <th style="width: 110px;">Severity</th>
                <th style="width: 220px;">Fix</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>KalenderScreen</strong></td>
                <td>Period prediction messes up when the user inputs a new period that is still ongoing.</td>
                <td>Visibility of system status</td>
                <td><span class="sev s3"><span class="bar"></span>3 (High)</span></td>
                <td>Improve visibility/handling of ongoing periods so predictions update correctly.</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td><strong>Start</strong></td>
                <td>Application name is missing.</td>
                <td>Consistency and standards</td>
                <td><span class="sev s1"><span class="bar"></span>1 (Low)</span></td>
                <td>Rename the app in the manifest.</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td><strong>Add entry page</strong></td>
                <td>Delete entry button is hidden.</td>
                <td>User control and freedom</td>
                <td><span class="sev s2"><span class="bar"></span>2 (Medium)</span></td>
                <td>Make the delete action visible and accessible.</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td><strong>Statistics page</strong></td>
                <td>Statistics colors don’t match the theme of the rest of the app.</td>
                <td>Consistency and standards</td>
                <td><span class="sev s2"><span class="bar"></span>2 (Medium)</span></td>
                <td>Adjust chart colors to align with the app theme.</td>
              </tr>

              <tr>
                <td><strong>All back buttons</strong></td>
                <td>Clicking back too many times leads to an empty / non-existing page.</td>
                <td>Error prevention / User control</td>
                <td><span class="sev s3"><span class="bar"></span>3 (High)</span></td>
                <td>Prevent repeated navigation (debounce/disable) and block invalid back stack.</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <div class="callout">
          <strong>Note:</strong> Severity scale used here is 1 (low) → 3 (high). You can adapt this to 0–4 if your course requires Nielsen’s standard severity scale.
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2><span class="icon">2</span> Hypotheses</h2>
        <div class="mini">
          <h3>Main hypothesis</h3>
          <p>
            Does the app help users predict and understand their <strong>mood</strong>, <strong>pain</strong>,
            <strong>energy levels</strong>, and <strong>period flow</strong> in a simple and easy-to-understand way?
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="mini" style="margin-top:10px;">
          <h3>Additional questions</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Is the app perceived as intuitive compared to other period tracking apps?</li>
            <li>Do users understand how to input data and interpret predictions?</li>
            <li>Do the visuals support understanding and reflection?</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="smallgrid">
          <div class="mini">
            <h3>Independent Variable (IV)</h3>
            <p>Quiet Bloom compared to another existing period tracking app.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="mini">
            <h3>Dependent Variable (DV)</h3>
            <p>Usability of the app.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <div class="grid three">
      <section>
        <h2><span class="icon">3</span> Data Collection</h2>
        <div class="mini">
          <h3>Quantitative</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Task completion rate</li>
            <li>Time needed to complete tasks</li>
            <li>Number of errors or misunderstandings</li>
            <li>System Usability Scale (SUS) score</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="mini" style="margin-top:10px;">
          <h3>Qualitative</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>Think-aloud comments during tasks</li>
            <li>Interview feedback on predictions and statistics</li>
            <li>Feedback on visual design (icons, colors, layout)</li>
            <li>Subjective impressions of accuracy and usefulness</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2><span class="icon">4</span> Method</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Study design:</strong> Within-subject comparison (Quiet Bloom vs. another app)</li>
          <li><strong>Session type:</strong> Moderated usability testing</li>
          <li><strong>Protocol:</strong> Think-aloud</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout">
          Tip: Keep the comparison app consistent across participants (or clearly document which app each participant used).
        </div>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2><span class="icon">5</span> Participants</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>People who menstruate and are familiar with period tracking</li>
          <li>Small sample size (5+ participants) for formative usability testing</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout">
          If you recruit beyond friends, include a short screening checklist (period tracking experience, comfort with think-aloud, etc.).
        </div>
      </section>
    </div>

    <section>
      <h2><span class="icon">6</span> Tasks (Planned Sequence)</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Input data of your last period (blood flow + other symptoms). Then open your usual period app and compare how accurate it is.
          Then input the period before that and check again, and then the one before that.
          <span class="muted">(Ask for day differences between cycles.)</span>
        </li>
        <li>Input today’s symptoms (including mood) and add a journal entry.</li>
        <li>Find your average cycle length and average period length.</li>
        <li>Find the journal entries overview and edit an entry.</li>
        <li>Go to the calendar and delete today’s entry from there.</li>
        <li>Find and look at the graphs. Are they clear? How do you feel about them? Try the categories.</li>
        <li>Change your name and profile picture.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2><span class="icon">7</span> Interview Questions</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>How do you feel about the style of the app? Is it appealing to you?</li>
        <li>Is there anything missing?</li>
        <li>Would you use this app? Why?</li>
        <li>Would you use a section with recommendations about each cycle phase?</li>
        <li>Would you be interested in seeing your ovulation in the calendar?</li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </main>

